  <subsection xml:id="subsec-magfld_movcharge">
    <title> Magnetic Field of a Moving Charge: </title>
    <introduction>
      <p>
       	<me>
          \vec{B} =\frac{\mu_{o}}{4\pi}\frac{q\vec{v}\times\hat{r}}{r^{2}}  \quad 	(Vector)
        </me>
        <me>
          B =\frac{\mu_{o}}{4\pi}\frac{qv\sin\phi}{r^{2}}  \quad    	(Magnitudes) 
        </me>
            </p>
    </introduction>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-free_permblt">
      <title>Permeability of Free Space, <m>\mu_{o}</m></title>
      <p>
        The property of space which permit magnetic flux to pass through it is known as permeability. 
        It is a measure of relative increase or decrease in the resultant magnetic field inside 
        a material compared with the magnetizing field H in which the given material is located. 
        It is a constant of proportionality that exists between magnetic induction (magnetic 
        flux density) B and magnetic field intensity (magnetizing field) H. For free space 
        <me>
          \mu_{o}= 4\pi\times10^{-7} \,W_{b}/A.m 
        </me>
         	<me>
            = 4\pi\times10^{-7} \,Henry/m = 1.2566\times10^{-6} \,H/m 
          </me>
          	<me>
              c =\frac{1}{\sqrt{\epsilon_{o}\mu_{o}}}
            </me>
           Materials may be classified magnetically on the basis of their permeabilities. 
           Materials that cause the lines of flux to move farther apart, resulting in a 
           decrease in magnetic flux density compared with a vacuum, are called <term>diamagnetic</term>. 
           Materials that concentrate magnetic flux by a factor of more than 1 but less than or equal 
           to 10 are called <term>paramagnetic</term>; materials that concentrate the flux by a 
           factor of more than 10 are called <term>ferromagnetic</term>. The  permeability 
           factors of some substances change with rising or falling temperature, or with the intensity 
           of the applied magnetic field. Permeability is often expressed in relative, rather than in 
           absolute, terms. If <m>\mu_{o}</m> be the permeability of free space, <m> \mu</m> be the 
           permeability of the given substance, then the relative permeability, <m>\mu_{r} </m>, is given by:
           <me>
            \mu_{r} = \frac{\mu}{\mu_{o}} 
           </me>
             </p>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-biot_savrt">
      <title>Magnetic Field of a Current Element (Biot Savart Law)</title>
      <p>
        Magnetic field, <m>\,dB</m> due a small current element of length, <m>\,dl</m> is given by
        <me>
          \vec{dB} =\frac{\mu_{o}}{4\pi}\frac{I\vec{dl}\times\hat{r}}{r^{2}} \quad (Differential) 
        </me>
        where <m>\hat{r}</m> is a unit vector along the direction of <m>\vec{r}.</m> 
        This law only works for a small current element. To find the magnetic field at a point 
        due to entire current carrying conductor, we need to integrate the the above equation for the total length of the conductor.
        <me>
          \vec{B} =\frac{\mu_{o}}{4\pi}\int\frac{I\vec{dl}\times\hat{r}}{r^{2}} \quad (Integral)
        </me>
            </p>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-stwire_magf">
      <title>Magnetic Field of a straight wire</title>
      <p>
        <me>
          \vec{\,dB} =\frac{\mu_{o}I}{4\pi}\frac{2a}{x\sqrt{x^{2}+a^{2})}}  \quad  	\text{(Right Hand Rule)} 
        </me>
        <me>
          B = \frac{\mu_{o}I}{2\pi r}\quad  	\text{(Right Hand Rule)}
        </me>
             </p> 
             <figure>
              <caption></caption>
              <sidebyside widths="35% 25%">
                <figure xml:id="fig51">
                  <caption></caption>
                  <image source="fig51.png"/>
              </figure>
                  <figure xml:id="rtgripmag">
                      <caption></caption>
                      <image source="rtgripmag.png"/>
                  </figure>
                   </sidebyside>
            </figure>
             <p>
              Consider a current carrying straight conductor of length  2a.  
              To find a magnetic field at a point P from the conductor consider a small current 
              element <m> \,dy</m> on a conductor and use Biot-Savart's law, 
              <me>
                \vec{\,dB}=\frac{\mu_{o}I}{4\pi}\frac{\vec{\,dy}\times\hat{r}}{r^{2}} (-\hat{k})
              </me>
              The direction of magnetic field at  P  is given by right hand grip rule which is going 
              into the plane of the paper. <m>\hat{r} </m> is unit vector along <m>\vec{r}</m> 
              and <m>\theta</m> is angle between current element and line joining the current element to point P. 
              <me>
                \text{or,}\quad \,dB=\frac{\mu_{o}I}{4\pi}\frac{\,dy\sin\theta}{r^{2}}  =\frac{\mu_{o}I}{4\pi}\frac{x}{r}\frac{\,dy}{r^{2}}
              </me>
              <me>
                = \frac{\mu_{o}I}{4\pi}\frac{x\,dy}{r^{3}}   =\frac{\mu_{o}I}{4\pi}\frac{x\,dy}{(x^{2}+y^{2})^{3/2}}
              </me>
                 <m>[\because \quad r^{2}=x^{2}+y^{2}]</m>
              <men xml:id="eqn-biot1">
                \therefore \quad B = \int \,dB=\frac{\mu_{o}I x}{4\pi}\int\limits_{-a}^{a}\frac{\,dy}{(x^{2}+y^{2})^{3/2}} 
              </men>
            Now solve the integrand first with the help of geometry of the figure then substitute the value to obtain B. 
            <me>
              \tan\phi = \frac{y}{x}
            </me>
            <me>
              \text{or,}\quad y=x\tan\phi
            </me>
            <me>
              \text{or,}\quad \,dy=x\sec^{2}\phi\,d\phi
            </me>
            <me>
              \therefore \quad \mathscr{I} = \int \frac{\,dy}{(x^{2}+y^{2})^{3/2}}  = \int \frac{x \sec^{2}\phi\,d\phi}{\left[x^{2}(1+\tan^{2}\phi)\right]^{3/2}}
            </me>
               <me>
              = \int\frac{x\sec^{2}\phi\,d\phi}{x^{3}\sec^{3}\phi} = \frac{1}{x^{2}}\int\cos\phi\,d\phi
            </me>
            <me>
              \text{or,}\quad \mathscr{I} = \frac{1}{x^{2}}\sin\phi  =\frac{1}{x^{2}}\frac{y}{r} =\frac{y}{x^{2}\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}}
            </me>
            </p>
          <p>
            <ol marker="a.">
              <li>
                <me>
                  \therefore \quad B = \frac{\mu_{o}I x}{4\pi}\left[\frac{y}{x^{2}\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}}\right]_{-a}^{a}
                </me>
                <me>
                  =\frac{\mu_{o}I}{4\pi} \left[\frac{2a}{x\sqrt{x^{2}+a^{2}}}\right]
                </me>
              </li>
              <li> 
                When <m> x \lt \lt a</m> (ie., for infinitely long wire) then <m> 1 \lt \lt \frac{a}{x} </m>, hence
                <me>
                  B = \frac{\mu_{o}I}{4\pi} \left[\frac{2a}{x\cdot x\sqrt{1+\frac{a^{2}}{x^{2}}}}\right] 
                </me>
                <me>
                  = \frac{\mu_{o}I}{4\pi}\frac{2a}{x^{2}\sqrt{\frac{a^{2}}{x^{2}}}} =\frac{\mu_{o}I}{4\pi} \frac{2a}{x}
                </me>
                <me>
                  \therefore \quad  B=  \frac{\mu_{o}I }{2\pi x} 
                </me>
                  </li> 
                  <li>
                    When <m> x \gt \gt a</m> then <m>\frac{x}{a} \gt \gt 1</m>, hence  
                    <me>
                      B =  \frac{\mu_{o}I }{2\pi} \frac{a}{x^{2}} \simeq 0 
                    </me>
                      </li>
            </ol>
                 </p>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-magcrnt_loop">
      <title>Magnetic field due to a current loop</title>
      <p>
        <me>
          B = \frac{\mu_{o}NIa^{2}}{2(x^{2}+a^{2})^{3/2}}
        </me>
        on axis of Coil with N turns.
        <me>
          B = \frac{\mu_{o}NI}{2a}
        </me>
        at center of Coil with N turns.
        Magnetic field at a point  P  due to a current element  <m>\,dl</m>  is given by 
        <me>
          \vec{\,dB} = \frac{\mu_{o}I}{4\pi}\frac{\vec{\,dl}\times\hat{r}}{r^{2}}
        </me>
        From Biot-Savart's law and is directed normal to the plane subtends by <m>\,dl</m> and <m>r</m>. 
        <me>
          \text{or,}\quad \vec{\,dB} = \frac{\mu_{o}I}{4\pi}\frac{\,dl\sin90^{o}}{r^{2}}
        </me>
        angle between <m>\,dl</m> and <m>r</m> is <m>90^{o}</m> 
        <me>
          \text{or,}\quad \,dB = \frac{\mu_{o}I}{4\pi}\frac{\,dl}{r^{2}}
        </me>
         </p>
         <figure xml:id="magring">
          <caption></caption>
          <image source="magring.png" width="35%"/>
      </figure>
         <p>
          Due to symmetry of current along the ring y components of field cancel 
          out but x component survived, hence 
          <me>
            \,dB\sin\phi=\frac{\mu_{o}I}{4\pi}\frac{\,dl}{r^{2}}\frac{a}{r} 
          </me>
          <me>
            = \frac{\mu_{o}I}{4\pi}\frac{\,dl a}{r^{3}} =  \frac{\mu_{o}I}{4\pi} \frac{a\,dl}{(a^{2}+x^{2})^{3/2}}
          </me>
          <me>
            \therefore\quad B= \int\,dB = \int\limits_{0}^{2\pi a}\frac{\mu_{o}I}{4\pi} \frac{a\,dl}{(a^{2}+x^{2})^{3/2}}
          </me>
          <me>
            =\frac{\mu_{o}I}{4\pi} \frac{a}{(a^{2}+x^{2})^{3/2}} \left[l\right]_{0}^{2\pi a}  = \frac{\mu_{o}I}{4\pi} \frac{a (2\pi a)}{(a^{2}+x^{2})^{3/2}}
          </me>
            <me>
            B= \frac{\mu_{o}I}{2} \frac{a^{2}}{(a^{2}+x^{2})^{3/2}}
          </me>
          If number of turns in a circular loop is N, then 
          <men xml:id="eqn-magring1">
            B=\frac{\mu_{o}I N a^{2}}{2(a^{2}+x^{2})^{3/2}} 
          </men>
          along the x-axis.
               </p>
               <p>
                Magnetic field at the center (ie., x=0) of a current carrying loop is 
                <me>
                  B= \frac{\mu_{o}I N a^{2}}{2a^{3}}=\frac{\mu_{o}I N }{2a}
                </me>
              </p>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-helmholtz">
      <title>Magnetic field at the center of a Helmholtz coil</title>
      <p>
        Helmholtz coils consist of two similar co-axial coils A and B having same radius, 
        same number of turns, and placed parallel to each other at a distance equal to their 
        radii as shown in <xref ref="helmholtz"/>. When the coils are connected in such a way 
        that the current flows through the coils in the same direction, then Helmholtz coils 
        produce nearly uniform magnetic field over a considerable region between the coils.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="helmholtz">
        <caption></caption>
        <image source="helmholtz.png" width="35%"/>
    </figure>
      <p>
        Magnetic field at the axial point at a distance x from the center of the coil 
        of radius a,  number of turns N, and carrying current I is given by 
        <men xml:id="eqn-helm1">
          B=\frac{\mu_{o}NIa^{2}}{2\left(a^{2}+x^{2}\right)^{3/2}} 
        </men>
        along x-axis.  
      </p>
      <p>
        The rate of variation of magnetic field  B  along x-axis is given by 
        <me>
          \frac{\,dB_{x}}{\,dx}=\frac{\,d}{\,dx}\left[\frac{\mu_{o}NIa^{2}}{2\left(a^{2}+x^{2}\right)^{3/2}}\right] 
        </me>
        <me>
          =\frac{\mu_{o} NIa^{2}}{2} \left[-\frac{3}{2} \left(a^{2}+x^{2}\right)^{-5/2}\cdot 2x \right]
        </me>
        <me>
          \therefore\quad \frac{\,dB_{x}}{\,dx}=-\frac{3}{2}\mu_{o} NIa^{2} \left[ \left(a^{2}+x^{2}\right)^{-5/2}\cdot x \right]
        </me>
        For uniform variation of <m>B_{x}</m>,  <m>\frac{\,dB_{x}}{\,dx} </m> must be constant 
        and <m>\frac{\,d^{2}B_{x}}{\,dx^{2}} </m> must be zero. Hence, 
        <me>
          \frac{\,d^{2}B_{x}}{\,dx^{2}}= -\frac{3}{2}\mu_{o} NIa^{2} \left[ \left(a^{2}+x^{2}\right)^{-5/2}-5x^{2}\left(a^{2}+x^{2}\right)^{-7/2} \right] = 0
        </me>
        <me>
          \text{or,}\quad -\frac{3}{2}\mu_{o} NIa^{2}  \left(a^{2}+x^{2}\right)^{-7/2}\left[a^{2}+x^{2}-5x^{2}\right] = 0
        </me>
        <me>
          \text{or,}\quad a^{2}-4x^{2} = 
        </me>
        <me>
          \therefore\quad x=\pm\frac{a}{2}
        </me>
        Thus, the rate of variation of magnetic field is constant at distance   
        <me>
          x=\pm\frac{a}{2}
        </me>
         from the center of the coil. Therefore on either side of point P, the field 
         due to one coil decreases uniformly, while that due to another is increases 
         uniformly. Since both the coils are identical and carry the same amount of current 
         in same direction the decrease in field due to one coil is balanced by the 
         increase in field by another one. Hence overall magnetic field remains uniform 
         over a considerable region on either side of the point P. The resultant magnetic 
         field B  between the region of coils are obtained by substituting the value of 
       <m> x=\frac{a}{2} </m> in eqn. <xref ref="eqn-helm1"/>. We have 
         <me>
          B=2\left.B_{x}\right\vert_{x=\frac{a}{2}}
         </me>
         <me>
          = 2\times \frac{\mu_{o}NIa^{2}}{2\left(a^{2}+\frac{a^{2}}{4}\right)^{3/2}} 
         </me>
         <me>
          = \frac{8\mu_{o}NI}{5^{3/2}a} =\frac{8\mu_{o}NI}{\sqrt{125}a}
         </me>
           </p>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-solenoid_curnt">
      <title>Magnetic field at a point due to current carrying solenoid</title>
      <p>
        Solenoid is a long wire wound in a closed-packed helix which behaves as a 
        magnet when carrying an electric current. Magnetic field is directed along 
        the axis of solenoid and can be determined by right hand grip rule [<xref ref="subsubsec-solenoid"/>].
      </p>
      <p>
        Consider a solenoid of radius a, number of turns per unit length n and a 
        length of current element <m>\,dl,</m>  so that total number of turns in 
        strip ABCD is <m>N = n\,dl</m>.  If current I is flowing through a solenoid 
        then the field at point P due to current element <m>\,dl</m>  is given by 
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="solenoid2">
        <caption></caption>
        <image source="solenoid2.png" width="50%"/>
    </figure>
      <p>
        <me>
          \,dB= \frac{\mu_{o}IN a^{2}}{2(a^{2}+x^{2})^{3/2}}
        </me>
        from eqn. <xref ref="eqn-magring1"/>
      <me>
        \therefore\quad \,dB= \frac{\mu_{o}I(n\,dl) a^{2}}{2(a^{2}+x^{2})^{3/2}}
      </me>
      From <m>\triangle CDE,</m> 
      <m> \sin\phi=\frac{CE}{CD}.</m> 
      <me>
        \text{or,}\quad CD= \,dl=\frac{CE}{\sin\phi} = \frac{r\,d\phi}{\sin\phi} = r\,d\phi\csc\phi
      </me>
          <me>
        \text{also,}\quad r^{2} = a^{2}+x^{2}
      </me>
      <me>
        \text{and}\quad  \sin\phi= \frac{a}{r}
      </me>
      <me>
        \therefore\quad \,dB =\frac{\mu_{o}(nr\,d\phi\csc\phi)I a^{2}}{2r^{3}} = \frac{\mu_{o}nI}{2}\frac{a^{2}}{r^{2}}\csc\phi\,d\phi
      </me>
          <me>
        =\frac{\mu_{o}nI}{2}\sin^{2}\phi\csc\phi\,d\phi =\frac{\mu_{o}nI}{2}\sin\phi\,d\phi
      </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          <me>
            \therefore\quad B=\frac{\mu_{o}nI}{2}\int\limits_{\alpha}^{\beta}\sin\phi\,d\phi
          </me>
          <me>
            = \frac{\mu_{o}nI}{2}\left(-\cos\phi\right)_{\alpha}^{\beta} =\frac{\mu_{o}nI}{2}\left(\cos\alpha-\cos\beta\right)
          </me>
          For an infinitely long solenoid, <m>\alpha\rightarrow 0, \quad \beta\rightarrow \pi. </m> Hence, 
          <me>
            B=\frac{\mu_{o}nI}{2}\left(1+1\right) = \mu_{o}nI
          </me>
          If point  P  is at the end of a solenoid,  <m>\alpha\rightarrow \frac{\pi}{2}, \quad \beta\rightarrow \pi.</m> 
          Hence, 
          <me>
            B=\frac{\mu_{o}nI}{2}
          </me>
          Thus for a long solenoid the magnetic field at the ends is half of that at the middle of the solenoid.
        </p>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>
  </section>

